**Addendum 7376-A-3: Interview Log C2**

[[div class="blockquote"]]

**Date:** 04/02/2000

**Interviewed:** SCP-7376-C

**Interviewer:** Dr. Safiya Light //(Director, Tactical Theology)//

----

**SCP-7376-C:** If I am to speak of my brother, I must first provide context.

I was not the first man to be born, though my people—the citizens of the great kingdom Edinnu—were perhaps among the first. Edinnu was not a vast domain, but it held claim to a great nexus of commerce and a fierce enough army to keep the [[[daevite-hub | Daeva]]] away from our borders.

My mother was Lilith, Edinnu's queen. She was an incredible sorceress, taught by the Serpent itself. Such was the strength of her magic, that each word she spoke resonated with the mutterings of thunder. My father was Adam, an escaped slave of the Daevite high gardens. Despite the circumstances of how he learned the craft, he never did lose his love of gardening--I remember him as being a very gentle man.

**Dr. Light:** Sounds like quite an odd couple.

**SCP-7376-C:** //[Chuckling.]// They were, indeed--but they found their own sort of equilibrium.

They raised me in Edinnu's capital, Paradisum. It was called The City Beneath Two Trees, as when it was first founded, my parents planted a pair of seeds at its heart: one, the seed of an ash tree from the Wanderer's Library and the other, a seed from the high gardens that had been cleansed of all Daevite corruption. It was a truly beautiful place...

//[Silence.]//

Anyway, I was the eldest of five children. I got along fine with each of my younger siblings—Set, Awan, and Azura—but I was always closest to Hevel, the secondborn of my family.

Hevel was... to say he was an inspiration is to shame him with faint praise. He was the best of us. A skilled warrior, a cunning strategist, a brilliant artist... he would even come to inherit a fragment of my mother's voice. Though he lacked the talent for magecraft, he, to her endless pride, learned to enchant his words so that all living things, even simple beasts, could understand his speech. And above all else, he was endlessly, genuinely //kind//. The kindest person I have ever known.

**Dr. Light:** You admired him.

**SCP-7376-C:** I //resented// him. He was everything I could not be—everything I had never //tried// to be out of base fear and apathy. I cared for him, yes—but that resentment was always smoldering in the back of my mind.

As we grew, it became clear that Hevel was likely to inherit my mother's throne, despite my being the firstborn. Knowing this, knowing that it was because he truly deserved it, had done far more to earn such station, fanned the embers of that resentment into a flame of animosity.

Then one day, my family received a message from none other than Grand Karcist Ion, appealing for our assistance in his rebellion against the enslaving Daevites. It was a message that went unanswered; for all my mother's strength, she knew that we had only kept the Daeva away by being too much of a hassle to overthrow. To affiliate ourselves with the Grand Karcist would be nothing less than a declaration of war--a war we would likely not survive. My father was of the same mind. Though his heart bled for his kinsmen, his duty to the people of Edinnu came first.

That night, Hevel came to me in secret, his countenance etched with doubt. Though he had never lived the life of a Daevite slave, he had always felt connected to them through our father. They were family to him, even if only as distant relations, and he could not stand the thought of their endless suffering. Now that he had heard their plea for help, he could no longer continue to do nothing--but he did not know what to do.

When he asked for my advice, I am ashamed to say that I saw only opportunity. I told him that our parents would never allow him to fight for the Daevite slaves as a prince of Edinnu--but if he were to leave in secret, representing not a kingdom but his own will... who knows what he could accomplish?

"And if you are to die," I did not say. "Killed by some nameless soldier on a distant battlefield, leaving behind an empty throne for your older, more deserving brother... then all the better."

And he believed me.

Years passed. I do not remember how many. A decade, maybe. Perhaps two.

Eventually, the day came when I heard word that Hevel, the conquering prince, had returned. Filled with a sickening mixture of joy and disappointment and shame, I rushed from the palace to greet him.

We reunited just as he crossed the city's far borders, meeting in a field on the outskirts of Paradisum. And I...

//[Silence.]//

**Dr. Light:** That's when it happened, wasn't it?

**SCP-7376-C:** He told me that he had succeeded in his quest. He had helped free the victims of the cruel Daeva--and more than that. He had met the Grand Karcist, and in doing so had come to forge a bond I did not understand. He had been named the Ozi̮rmok's Võlutaar.

I heard this and knew—with total certainty—that in trying to win back my throne, I had only crushed what little chance I had. In becoming a true hero of the people, in bonding with the leader of a nation that was on the verge of becoming the most powerful in the known world, the throne was already as good as his.

I knew this, and in my fear and hatred and rage and all-consuming //entitlement//, I...

I told him that I was overjoyed to see him returned safe to us. That I was proud of him. That we would return to the palace together. And when he turned to walk alongside me, I picked up a heavy stone from the field and...

//[Silence.]//

Well. Everyone knows how this story ends.

**Dr. Light:** Is that really how it ended?

//[Silence.]//

**SCP-7376-C:** No. That is when the trouble truly began.

**Dr. Light:** Tell me what happened next.

**SCP-7376-C:** My crime was quickly discovered. I was stripped of my family name, cursed twice over, and banished. So I...

//[Silence.]//

What you need to understand is that I wasn't particularly remorseful, back then. I was not--an entirely pleasant person, in my youth. I regretted what I had done, certainly. I regretted getting caught, regretted losing my station and my family, but as for proper guilt for the harm I had caused?

//[SCP-7376-C makes a seesaw motion with his hand.]//

The feeling wasn't //absent//, but it was not at the front of my mind, either. So when Hevel died, I saw it less as a wrongdoing demanding penance and more a problem needing solution.

**Dr. Light:** You wanted to bring Hevel back to life.

**SCP-7376-C:** It was not as difficult as I imagined it would; the hardest part would be in the grave robbing.

After I had obtained Hevel's corpse, I found an necro-chemist to stop its decomposition and undo what little rot it had already endured.

Then, I bought the services of a spirit-caller to pull Hevel's soul from the ether and bind it to his body. Normally, such an act should only be possible in the first few moments after death, but the souls of those who died violently tend to linger for a time... especially so for those killed by their loved ones.

All that remained was to give him a spark of life... but I was greedy. Just resurrecting him wasn't enough for me.

And so I began my journey to Adytum, capital city of Kalmaktama. To Grand Karcist Ion.

